<DOC><DOCNO>WSJ910116-0098</DOCNO><DOCID>910116-0098.</DOCID><HL>   Retail Sales Fell   0.4% in December   Rose 3.6% in Year   ----   By Paul Duke Jr.   Staff Reporter of The Wall Street Journal</HL><DATE>01/16/91</DATE><SO>WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE A2</SO><IN>BROADLINE RETAILERS, DEPARTMENT STORES (RTB)SPECIALTY APPAREL RETAILERS (SAP)SPECIALTY RETAILERS (OTS)ECONOMIC NEWS (ECO)U.S. ECONOMIC INDICATORS (EMI)</IN><LP>   WASHINGTON -- Retail sales fell 0.4% in December, theCommerce Department reported, in yet another sign that theeconomy contracted in the fourth quarter.   The decrease in December means retail sales for 1990 roseonly 3.6%, which was the smallest annual increase since a 3%gain in 1982, the last time the economy was in recession. TheDecember slide, to $151.06 billion, followed a 0.1% drop inNovember. Sales for 1990 totaled $1.799 trillion.</LP><TEXT>   With other economic reports indicating the economy entereda downturn in the past few months, the sales drop wasn'tunexpected.   A major factor was weakness in auto sales, which fell 1.4%last month. But several other areas also saw consumers pullback. Sales at apparel and accessory stores dropped 2%, whilegeneral merchandise stores, which include department stores,saw a 0.9% drop. The figures are adjusted for seasonalvariations, such as the effect of the Christmas season, butnot for inflation.   With oil prices coming down somewhat in December, sales atgasoline stations dropped 3.1% for the month. But for theyear service station sales were up 18.7%, largely because ofthe earlier jump in oil prices caused by Iraq's invasion ofKuwait in August. Sales at drug stores rose 1.9% in Decemberand were up 14% for the year.   Sales of durable goods, items expected to last more thanthree years, dropped 0.8% after a 1.1% decline in November.Sales of nondurable goods fell 0.1%, following a 0.5%increase in November.</TEXT></DOC>